text: I've noticed this since the first trailer for this film, but the whole concept of "Your inner circle has been compromised, we are on the brink of war, trust no one" is literally the core of Winter Soldier's premise. While the themes might not be the same in terms of being haunted by the ghosts of your past and unknowingly serving the evil you fought against, there is major overlap and Marvel was trying to cash in on the success from Winter Soldier as their best movie to save themselves. I'll still watch this since the The Winter Soldier is an all time favorite of mine, but I hope it has some originality and can still be good.

text:
Positives : 
Gal Gadot look stunning.
Zegler can sing.

Negatives.
You tried to hide it, but you can still tell that this is a girl boss movie. 
Thematically this would not be an issue but, unfortunately the actress playing Snow White made it impossible to separate the character from the actress. 

She might have very well played the best Snow White on screen but many will see a "Mean, Disrespectful, and very Unlikeable" person as Snow White.
That will ultimately hurt sales for this movie.

The CG in the movie looks really good in certain scenes, but more often then not, pulls you out of immersion with really bad uncanny valley images. The Dwarves in particular just didn't quite translate well during the animation process, they really should have used live actors.

All in all, hope that those who can enjoy this movie will do so, for me, Snow White's departure from the true innocent as portrayed in the original movie and the radical change to the story (and in essence, the soul of this story) is just too much of a stretch and neither I nor my family will be supporting it.

text: I remember seeing scar's paw come crashing down in the theater opening night in a packed theater in 1994. We had all just finished watching the circle of life scene and were still not sold on the film we were all like what the heck is this movie musical about lions? The movie changed my life at the time and still resonates to this day. I can watch it again and again and can recite the entire movie in the voice of the characters w/o a script. text: For those who don't know: Bong Joon Ho is one of the best directors in the world, straight up. He rivals Park Chan Wook as the best director working in South Korea. His best movie is Memories of Murder, but he's also made several others including The Host, Snowpiercer, Okja, and Parasite. His movies are known for being disturbing and representing the dark side of humanity, but this one seems like he's going for a dark comedy/satirical approach which could work really well. I would strongly recommend watching his earlier movies so you can understand his vibe.

text: The movie initially had fascinating visuals and an intriguing atmosphere. However, the characters, especially the villain, felt too one-dimensional. The director seemed to aim for a metaphorical meaning, but it ended up feeling too boring and unengaging. Because of this, the story felt loose and predictable, making it easy to guess the ending. Reflecting on it now, the topic also feels too old-fashioned because there are already so many stories about cloning, and the director's effort to deliver that concept didn't resonate with me.

text: I liked the concept. It was creative. But it was bizarre like the Hitchhiker's Guide and seemingly without purpose as in the Guide. There were parallels to our life and death, but it lost the truthful angst of the question in its absurdist presentation. Obviously there was a moral to the story, about personal responsibility, coexistence vs ignorant violence and abuse. But the scenes with the leader, seemingly trying to depict someone we know, spoiled serious contemplation. Although it was fantastical, it lent itself to be more of a drama, a drama which stalled on a single storyline when the expendables idea could have continued bringing in fresh plot twists. Yet it didn't. The Menu had extreme unlikely activity but it stayed real so we could sink ourselves into the idea. If Mickey was to just be odd and quirky with cartoon co-stars it needed to go even farther. Even cartoons evolve with incredible imagination. Either way it didn't invest. You can't just make up for a missing movie by playing simplistic narration and being grotesque.

text: It seems like they made this trailer in response to the complaints of the previous one. The only line Kraven has is in russian this time, which conceals that he has no accent whatsoever. Not sure what to believe here, but the first trailer probably has more reality in it.

text:
Way, way, WAY, better than expected! Sophie Thatcher has had her watershed moment. With this she is certainly on EVERYONE radar. She is the standout in an also excellent cast, the foil to Jack Quaids self-serving boorish, manipulative lout of a man-boy. (props to him as well) Its been a while since I have seen naivety, innocence, and vulnerability, contrasted with confidence and sense of purpose in Sophie as "Iris the Companion".
Certainly she sticks the landing, and also creates a compelling character, that I do hope we see more of in a possible sequel.

I have an amazing story. One day I was driving home, when all of a sudden the Lord came to me in spirit. I felt very close to Him. I knew if I asked him to play any song on the radio he would, I guess to bless my faith.
So I said "ok, Lord play "Come as you are". 
I turned on the radio and the song started playing right there on the spot, perfectly‚Ä¶
I started getting flooded with chills like a waterfall, crying, and trembling. 
He stayed with me for 10 minutes in my driveway. until I got outta the car.

Someone is using the monkey as a weapon, or the monkey is using them as an assistant. At 1:31, the person who brings the monkey into that shop can be seen stepping back and out of the way while staring at the monkey. This implies they know what‚Äôs it‚Äôs doing, which further implies that they brought it there knowing it would kill. text:
Where do I even begin? Oh, right, the exploding people. Yes, you read that correctly. Not just one exploding person, mind you, but a veritable symphony of exploding people. It's like the filmmakers decided to replace character development with a fireworks display of gore. And the gore? Let's just say it looked like they raided the clearance aisle of a Halloween prop store.

The script? It's less a script and more a collection of random grunts, screams, and the occasional, "Where's the monkey?" Said monkey, by the way, is a plush and plastic toy that apparently possesses the power to turn humans into fleshy pi√±atas. No explanation, no backstory, just... splat. It's like the writers were playing a game of Mad Libs with a horror movie plot and the results were, shall we say, "unique."

And the editing? Oh, the editing. They seem to have taken inspiration from a blender. We're treated to a rapid-fire montage of limbs, torsos, and close-ups of eyeballs, all set to a soundtrack that sounds like a dial-up modem having a seizure. It's less a movie and more a visual assault on the senses.

The "plot" (again, using that word generously) revolves around... well, I'm not entirely sure. Something about a cursed monkey toy and a group of people who apparently won a contest to see who could make the worst life choices. The acting is on par with a high school play performed by sleepwalkers.

Honestly, I'm baffled. I'm genuinely perplexed as to how this film got made. Did someone accidentally fund a fever dream? Did a group of toddlers take over a film set? I have so many questions, and none of them involve the monkey.

"Monkey" isn't just bad; it's an insult to bad movies. It's the cinematic equivalent of a moldy sandwich left in a hot car. It's a testament to the fact that sometimes, money is indeed wasted. If you value your sanity, your time, or your ability to enjoy any other movie ever made, stay far, far away from "Monkey." You've been warned.
